const faqs = [
  { q: "Can I borrow against an independent watch without selling it?", a: "Potentially. A watch-secured loan may provide liquidity without an immediate sale. Ownership, possession and permitted use depend on the security, custody, insurance and movement terms. Approval still depends on the borrower, the exact watch, the evidence file and the proposed transaction." },
  { q: "How do lenders decide how much an independent or complicated watch can support?", a: "There is no universal percentage. At ALYRA, the assessment starts with relevant completed sales, then adjusts for the exact reference, condition, originality, provenance and serviceability, deducts likely realisation costs and allows for time and market depth. ALYRA then applies its own advance, concentration and credit policy; other lenders may use different policies." },
  { q: "What is an independent watchmaker?", a: "The term generally describes a maker operating outside the major watch groups, but it covers a wide range from established manufactures to very small ateliers. Independence alone does not establish value or liquidity. Production history, collector demand, reference-level sales, service continuity and the authority of the maker's records remain important." },
  { q: "Do complications always make a watch more valuable?", a: "No. A complication is a function beyond telling the time, such as a chronograph, annual calendar, world time, perpetual calendar or minute repeater. It may add technical interest and scarcity, but condition, functionality, service cost, parts access and buyer demand determine whether it adds recoverable value." },
  { q: "Are box and papers essential for watch-backed lending?", a: "Not in every case, especially for older watches, but they can materially improve verification and marketability. ALYRA may also rely on invoices, archive extracts, maker confirmation, service records and specialist inspection. An incomplete file usually means more due diligence and a wider uncertainty allowance." },
  { q: "Does polishing reduce a watch's lending value?", a: "It can. Polishing may remove metal, soften case lines or alter original finishes, while dial repainting or replacement parts can reduce collector interest. The effect depends on the reference, the quality and extent of the work, and how much originality the relevant buyer market expects." },
  { q: "Can a unique or prototype watch be good collateral?", a: "Possibly, but uniqueness can make valuation harder because there may be no repeatable comparable sales. Strong provenance, maker confirmation and broad specialist interest may help, while one charity or celebrity result may not be reproducible. A lender may therefore require a larger uncertainty margin despite the watch's importance." },
  { q: "Why does serviceability matter for independent watches?", a: "A buyer needs confidence that the watch can be maintained and repaired. Some makers require official service routes or tightly control parts and warranty work. Long turnaround times, limited capacity or uncertain support can reduce net proceeds and the number of willing buyers." },
